":"The explanation of this tool is quite simple. It leverages Netlify's built-in redirect system to create a custom route and take you to the desired external address. Then it auto-commits and pushes your code to the remote Git repository (e.g Github)."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you have your Netlify site connected to the repo, it will trigger a new build, making your short link available to the world in a few seconds."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"getting-it-to-work"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Getting it to work"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The first step is forking the repo and then setting up the Netlify site. Then just sync both. You don't need any paid Netlify features or complex setup."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Then clone the repo locally. Not strictly necessary, but I personally recommend to "},{"type":"element","tag":"code-inline","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"npm link"}]},{"type":"text","value":" the folder after cloning the repo. This will make the locally installed package available everywhere in your PC, allowing you to just run the CLI command and automatically doing the rest, even if you're not in that folder."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"trying-it-out"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Trying it out"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you named the linked binary \"shorten\":"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"code-inline","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"shorten https://example.com"}]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"will yield a random short string. Just like typical shorteners do."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"code-inline","props":{